CANINE DISTEMPER, WILDLIFE - CANADA: (ONTARIO) RACCOON
******************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>

Date: 15 Oct 2010
Source: The Daily News [edited]
<http://www.chathamdailynews.ca/ArticleDisplay.aspx?e=2800543>


Animal behaviour suggests disease outbreak
------------------------------------------
There is growing concern about a possible outbreak of distemper in the
raccoon population in southwestern Ontario.

Holly Simpson of Chatham, a biologist with the Ministry of Natural
Resources, said on Thursday [14 Oct 2010] that some raccoons in the wild
are exhibiting abnormal behaviour, which is consistent with distemper or
rabies. "It's entirely possible," she said.

Simpson said she's received a large number of calls from the public
expressing concern about raccoons. Simpson said people should take
precautions to keep their pets shielded from wild raccoons. "We have sent a
couple of raccoon carcasses from Harwich to the University of Guelph for
analysis but so far haven't heard word," she said.

Simpson said several callers have suggested raccoons in the wild don't
appear to be healthy and are displaying unusual actions.

Paul Praill of Chatham, a hunter and trapper, said there appears to be a
large number of dead raccoons along the roadways. "I'm told there is a
rampant case of distemper among the raccoon population and it's causing
them to act in strange fashion," he said.

Praill said raccoons have been seen walking around yards and field in
circles, chasing people and coming out in daytime in large numbers. Praill
recommends hunters refrain from taking dead raccoons home with them. "They
are acting very, very unusual this fall," he said.

The Chatham-Kent Police Service said Thursday it has received a large
number of calls from citizens about raccoons. The calls, according to a
release, are generally complaints of raccoons in trees, backyards, sitting
near roadways looking at people. In consultation with the Ontario Society
for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals (OSPCA), the police service is
recommending that raccoon concerns be directed to the OSPCA.

The OSPCA specialize in adoptions, canine control, cruelty investigations,
lost and found and offer 24-hour emergency service.

[byline: Bob Boughner <bboughner@chathamdailynews.ca>]

