communicated by:
HealthMap alerts via ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Clinical signs of canine distemper in raccoons may include discharge from
the nose and eyes, a rough coat of hair, emaciated appearance, and unusual
behavior such as disorientation or wandering aimlessly. The animals' signs
become progressively worse and the disease is usually fatal. Distemper is
not the same disease as rabies, although some signs are similar.

Canine distemper runs its course rapidly. Distemper is often fatal and
death is usually attributed to a secondary infection such as pneumonia. Not
all raccoons get the disease and many survive the outbreaks.

Definitive diagnosis is based on laboratory analysis of affected tissues by
fluorescent antibody techniques.

The diseases can appear quite similar in raccoons. There are some people
who have seen distemper present as aggression, while others have only seen
the sick, disturbed, miserable looking creature. Perhaps it is a different
distemper strain since it is a virus, or perhaps it is individual
differences in the animals. However, the definitive diagnosis should always
be laboratory confirmation.

It is to be hoped that the authorities in this situation will be able to
clarify which disease they are currently dealing with.

Portions of this comment have been extracted from
<http://www.dfw.state.or.us/wildlife/diseases/distemper/> and
<http://www.state.tn.us/twra/pdfs/distemper.pdf> - Mod.TG

